1
00:00:00,260 --> 00:00:03,120
AI is forcing me to change
how I manage my money.

2
00:00:03,120 --> 00:00:05,160
You see, I've made millions from investing

3
00:00:05,160 --> 00:00:06,780
over the past 35 years,

4
00:00:06,780 --> 00:00:10,143
and most of that success has
come from one simple strategy.

5
00:00:10,143 --> 00:00:13,200
- An S&P 500 low-cost index fund.

6
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:14,730
- [News Reporter] S&P 500 index fund.

7
00:00:14,730 --> 00:00:16,107
- The S&P, American.

8
00:00:16,107 --> 00:00:16,940
- The S&P 500.

9
00:00:16,940 --> 00:00:18,570
- The S&P 500-

10
00:00:18,570 --> 00:00:21,840
- Has returned an average
of over 10% per year.

11
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:24,060
- This is known as passive investing,

12
00:00:24,060 --> 00:00:26,010
as your money automatically gets split

13
00:00:26,010 --> 00:00:29,400
between the top 500 companies in the USA.

14
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:32,520
So rather than having to
actively pick winning stocks,

15
00:00:32,520 --> 00:00:35,340
you instead just buy a
small piece of all of them.

16
00:00:35,340 --> 00:00:38,130
The idea is that even
if some stocks crash,

17
00:00:38,130 --> 00:00:39,900
owning lots of them protects you,

18
00:00:39,900 --> 00:00:42,960
and you still benefit as
the overall market grows.

19
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:45,090
I'm not gonna lie, over the years,

20
00:00:45,090 --> 00:00:48,300
this has been proven to
be a fantastic strategy.

21
00:00:48,300 --> 00:00:51,570
As I've said, I've earned
millions doing exactly this.

22
00:00:51,570 --> 00:00:53,550
However, after making my last video

23
00:00:53,550 --> 00:00:55,650
about a potential AI bubble,

24
00:00:55,650 --> 00:00:59,880
I sat down, reviewed my
investments, and made a few changes.

25
00:00:59,880 --> 00:01:02,040
So in this video, I'm gonna be revealing

26
00:01:02,040 --> 00:01:04,900
the five things I changed because of AI.

27
00:01:04,900 --> 00:01:06,960
(lively orchestral music)

28
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:08,070
Believe it or not,

29
00:01:08,070 --> 00:01:10,410
for every dollar you
invest into the S&P 500,

30
00:01:10,410 --> 00:01:14,370
40 cents of it will go
into just 10 companies.

31
00:01:14,370 --> 00:01:18,840
These companies are NVIDIA,
Microsoft, Apple, Alphabet,

32
00:01:18,840 --> 00:01:23,400
Amazon, Broadcom, Meta,
Tesla, Berkshire Hathaway,

33
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:25,190
and finally, JPMorgan.

34
00:01:25,190 --> 00:01:28,350
As of filming this video, these
companies currently make up

35
00:01:28,350 --> 00:01:31,980
a whopping 40% of the entire index fund.

36
00:01:31,980 --> 00:01:35,250
What's even more concerning
is that NVIDIA alone

37
00:01:35,250 --> 00:01:37,380
will get between seven to eight cents

38
00:01:37,380 --> 00:01:40,470
of every dollar you
invest into the S&P 500.

39
00:01:40,470 --> 00:01:41,850
This is because the index fund

40
00:01:41,850 --> 00:01:44,040
is called market-cap-weighted,

41
00:01:44,040 --> 00:01:47,190
which simply means the more
valuable a company becomes,

42
00:01:47,190 --> 00:01:49,440
the bigger slice of the fund it takes up.

43
00:01:49,440 --> 00:01:51,810
So what's actually causing these companies

44
00:01:51,810 --> 00:01:53,460
to become more and more valuable?

45
00:01:53,460 --> 00:01:55,860
Well, if we put Berkshire Hathaway

46
00:01:55,860 --> 00:01:58,590
and JPMorgan to one side for a moment

47
00:01:58,590 --> 00:02:01,260
because they don't really
fit the same pattern,

48
00:02:01,260 --> 00:02:03,540
something interesting starts to happen.

49
00:02:03,540 --> 00:02:05,910
What we're left with
is a group of companies

50
00:02:05,910 --> 00:02:08,730
that share one very specific trait.

51
00:02:08,730 --> 00:02:12,450
They're all spending aggressively
on the same thing: AI.

52
00:02:12,450 --> 00:02:14,640
You might be thinking, "That's great.

53
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:17,670
AI is the future, so
this all makes sense."

54
00:02:17,670 --> 00:02:19,620
However, not so fast.

55
00:02:19,620 --> 00:02:21,390
For all these AI companies

56
00:02:21,390 --> 00:02:23,790
to justify their current valuations,

57
00:02:23,790 --> 00:02:26,910
they would need to make
around $2 trillion in revenue.

58
00:02:26,910 --> 00:02:28,620
To put that into perspective,

59
00:02:28,620 --> 00:02:32,010
that's more than NVIDIA, Microsoft, Apple,

60
00:02:32,010 --> 00:02:36,000
Alphabet, Amazon, and
Meta combined in 2024.

61
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:39,570
This shows these companies
at the top of the S&P 500

62
00:02:39,570 --> 00:02:41,880
aren't being valued based
on what they own today,

63
00:02:41,880 --> 00:02:44,730
but on what investors expect
them to earn in the future.

64
00:02:44,730 --> 00:02:47,490
Now, this isn't a major issue on its own,

65
00:02:47,490 --> 00:02:49,050
as it's very common for companies

66
00:02:49,050 --> 00:02:51,180
to be valued on their future potential.

67
00:02:51,180 --> 00:02:53,070
However, it is quite worrying

68
00:02:53,070 --> 00:02:55,380
when it's all linked to
one type of technology.

69
00:02:55,380 --> 00:02:58,860
These companies are all
essentially making the same bet

70
00:02:58,860 --> 00:03:00,630
that AI is the future,

71
00:03:00,630 --> 00:03:03,090
and they're financing
it with a ton of debt.

72
00:03:03,090 --> 00:03:05,730
A great example of this
is Sam Altman saying

73
00:03:05,730 --> 00:03:09,810
he's willing to commit
$1.4 trillion in spending

74
00:03:09,810 --> 00:03:11,220
for AI infrastructure,

75
00:03:11,220 --> 00:03:13,853
when his company, OpenAI,
is currently only making

76
00:03:13,853 --> 00:03:17,310
$13 to $20 billion in yearly revenue.

77
00:03:17,310 --> 00:03:20,370
A lot of this debt is also pretty hidden.

78
00:03:20,370 --> 00:03:22,470
As I discussed in my last video,

79
00:03:22,470 --> 00:03:24,930
these companies are
bumping up their valuations

80
00:03:24,930 --> 00:03:27,150
by passing money around to each other.

81
00:03:27,150 --> 00:03:29,100
It's a whole complicated mess.

82
00:03:29,100 --> 00:03:32,190
Long story short, it's all
a massive feedback loop

83
00:03:32,190 --> 00:03:33,780
that keeps reinforcing itself.

84
00:03:33,780 --> 00:03:36,540
Bigger companies attract
more passive investment,

85
00:03:36,540 --> 00:03:38,460
which pushes their prices higher,

86
00:03:38,460 --> 00:03:41,610
giving them a bigger share of the S&P 500,

87
00:03:41,610 --> 00:03:43,800
and therefore even more money to grow

88
00:03:43,800 --> 00:03:46,440
from passive index fund
investors just like us.

89
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:48,090
This is having a knock-on effect

90
00:03:48,090 --> 00:03:50,700
of making the US economy look strong.

91
00:03:50,700 --> 00:03:53,730
However, data from Deutsche
Bank actually argues

92
00:03:53,730 --> 00:03:56,250
that if it wasn't for
AI spending right now,

93
00:03:56,250 --> 00:03:58,140
then we'd already be in a recession.

94
00:03:58,140 --> 00:04:01,680
So what if instead of prioritizing
the biggest companies,

95
00:04:01,680 --> 00:04:03,300
we could spread our money equally

96
00:04:03,300 --> 00:04:06,030
across every company in the S&P 500?

97
00:04:06,030 --> 00:04:08,010
Well, we actually can

98
00:04:08,010 --> 00:04:12,840
with something called an
equal-weighted S&P 500 index fund,

99
00:04:12,840 --> 00:04:16,080
and on the surface, it looks
like the perfect solution.

100
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:20,070
Instead of having 40%
concentrated in the top 10 stocks,

101
00:04:20,070 --> 00:04:24,240
it's around 2% as every
company is treated equally.

102
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:26,010
By investing in something like this,

103
00:04:26,010 --> 00:04:28,080
there is no doubt that
you are less exposed

104
00:04:28,080 --> 00:04:31,080
to the potential AI bubble
that is currently forming.

105
00:04:31,080 --> 00:04:34,050
However, it's not the perfect solution

106
00:04:34,050 --> 00:04:35,610
because we're trying to limit the money

107
00:04:35,610 --> 00:04:37,170
going into larger companies,

108
00:04:37,170 --> 00:04:39,870
it might actually lead
to a much bigger problem,

109
00:04:39,870 --> 00:04:43,290
as it follows something called
a negative momentum approach,

110
00:04:43,290 --> 00:04:45,960
which sounds complicated,
but it's really not.

111
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:48,900
All it means is that when
a company in the S&P 500

112
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:52,230
starts to take off, think
Tesla during its big run,

113
00:04:52,230 --> 00:04:55,260
the fund automatically
sells some of it as it rises

114
00:04:55,260 --> 00:04:58,290
and uses that money to buy
companies that haven't gone up.

115
00:04:58,290 --> 00:05:00,660
So you're effectively selling the winners

116
00:05:00,660 --> 00:05:04,260
and buying the losers purely
to keep everything balanced.

117
00:05:04,260 --> 00:05:08,100
On the flip side, a
normal S&P 500 index fund

118
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:09,660
that's market-cap-weighted

119
00:05:09,660 --> 00:05:11,790
doesn't need to trade nearly as often.

120
00:05:11,790 --> 00:05:13,620
When a company gains momentum,

121
00:05:13,620 --> 00:05:16,650
it's simply allowed to take up
a bigger share of the index.

122
00:05:16,650 --> 00:05:18,180
Instead of trimming the winners,

123
00:05:18,180 --> 00:05:21,900
the fund gradually reduces
exposure to smaller companies

124
00:05:21,900 --> 00:05:23,790
to make room for the larger ones.

125
00:05:23,790 --> 00:05:25,170
But why does this matter?

126
00:05:25,170 --> 00:05:28,050
Well, the more a fund trades,
the higher the costs are.

127
00:05:28,050 --> 00:05:30,120
Therefore, it's something
that's often overlooked

128
00:05:30,120 --> 00:05:32,160
and can eat into your gains.

129
00:05:32,160 --> 00:05:34,500
That's why, although
I'm putting less money

130
00:05:34,500 --> 00:05:37,680
into the S&P 500, I'm
still keeping the majority

131
00:05:37,680 --> 00:05:39,510
of my stock market portfolio

132
00:05:39,510 --> 00:05:42,240
in the regular
market-cap-weighted version.

133
00:05:42,240 --> 00:05:46,080
So now I freed up some of
my money from the S&P 500.

